A StatefulSet requires a Headless Service to function correctly. While standard deployments use services to balance traffic across a pool of identical pods, a StatefulSet needs to give each individual pod a permanent, predictable network identity.

Here is a deep dive into why they are paired, how the networking works, and how to create them imperatively.

Why StatefulSets Require a Headless Service
In a standard Kubernetes Service, a single virtual IP address (the ClusterIP) acts as a load balancer, routing traffic randomly to any healthy pod.

A Headless Service explicitly sets clusterIP: None. Instead of routing traffic to a single virtual IP, a Headless Service modifies the internal DNS behavior of the cluster. When a client performs a DNS lookup on a Headless Service, CoreDNS returns a list of direct IP addresses for all pods matched by the selector.

Standard Service:  [Client] ---> [ClusterIP (10.96.0.1)] ---> (Random Pod)
Headless Service:  [Client] ---> [DNS Lookup] ---> Returns [Pod-0 IP, Pod-1 IP, Pod-2 IP]


By linking a StatefulSet to a Headless Service, Kubernetes automatically generates a stable, deterministic DNS A-record for every single pod using the formula:

pod-name.headless-service-name.namespace.svc.cluster.local

===============================================================================================

Step 1: Create the Headless Service
You can create a Headless Service imperatively by using the standard create service clusterip command and explicitly passing the --cluster-ip=None flag.

kubectl create service clusterip data-service \
  --cluster-ip=None \
    --tcp=27017:27017

Step 2: Create the StatefulSet Linked to the Service
Next, create the StatefulSet. Use the --service-name flag to point it directly to the Headless Service you just created.

kubectl create statefulset db-node \
  --image=mongo:6.0 \
    --replicas=3 \
      --service-name=data-service


Once both resources are running, you can inspect how the headless service exposes individual network endpoints.

1. Check the Pods and Endpoints
Observe that your pods are strictly indexed (db-node-0, db-node-1, db-node-2):

kubectl get pods -l app=db-node -o wide

If you inspect the endpoints of your headless service, you will see it tracks the raw, direct IP addresses of all three pods instead of masking them behind a single service IP:

kubectl get endpoints data-service



2. Test the DNS Lookup (The Definitive Test)
To see the headless magic in action, spin up a temporary interactive testing pod inside the cluster and run an nslookup on the service:

kubectl run dns-test --rm -i --tty --image=busybox:v1.36 -- restart=Never -- nslookup data-service

CoreDNS will return the individual A-records for every pod backend:

Name:   data-service.default.svc.cluster.local
Address: 10.244.0.12
Address: 10.244.0.13
Address: 10.244.1.5











